{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"3698e256-a0ed-456c-b213-d79356628230","content":"Run **`dotnet workload update`**. Here's why:\n\n- **`dotnet workload update`** — Downloads and installs the **latest versions** of all installed workloads to match your current SDK. After an SDK update, this is what brings workloads (like `maui`) back in sync.\n\n- **`dotnet workload repair`** — Reinstalls the **same versions** already recorded. It fixes corrupted installations but won't pull newer workload manifests needed by a newer SDK.\n\n**TL;DR:** SDK changed → versions are mismatched → you need `update`, not `repair`.\n\n```bash\ndotnet workload update\n```\n\nIf you still have issues afterward, also verify which workloads are installed with `dotnet workload list`.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"a294ad74-709e-4ecd-bb25-9e9cc35deb8c","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about the difference between `dotnet workload update` and `dotnet workload repair` to fix a build issue after a .NET SDK update. This is a general knowledge question — I don't need to search a codebase for this.","outputTokens":247,"requestId":"DC03:184190:86D4F:A92A8:69F54A2A"},"id":"32f4c684-3554-4651-b65c-d366de367930","timestamp":"2026-05-02T00:49:53.123Z","parentId":"9cee26fb-3577-47e3-8a3a-bf3f71a59c27"}
